reviewText: I came late to the series as I do not watch this type of program on T.V. It has a tendency to pass time and never get anywhere.Once you realize there is just a more recent "Days of Our Lives" and quit looking for a cohesive story, you can enjoy each unique episode. Just understand the there are no great insights just fun watching how they put it together. We have to create a psychological situation an antagonist and let the main character solve the situation all in 42 minutes.Looks closely and periodically there is product name recognition like "Cisco Systems."On season two they did the one thing that really irks me; Episode 12 and 13 have a "To be Continued".For those people contemplating the series or just interested here is a quickie overview of Eureka (2006 TV series). The down contains mostly scientific types that work for secret government project in a hidden facility nearby.  Someone or thing is always getting into trouble (mostly from experiments) and need a down-to-earth sheriff Jack Carter (Colin Ferguson) to help interpret and solve the problem.  Jack has problems of his own trying to relate to women, including his teenage daughter Zoe (Jordan Hinson). On the sinister side is some mysterious cabal who's only known member to us is psychiatrist Beverly Barlowe (Debrah Farentino).On season two things just get better. Other programs revert to old formulas and rehashes. This series becomes more intriguing.
summary: Great fun human interaction masked as sci-fi

reviewText: In most sci-fi shows, time travel is usually just a one-off deal that never has any lasting repercussions. But it forms the centerpiece of "Eureka Season 4.0," in which a single jaunt back in time causes sweeping changes for the citizens of Eureka -- it sounds like a cheap way of shaking things up, but the focus on what time travel has changed is pretty interesting.Carter (Colin Ferguson) is out jogging on Founder's Day when he suddenly goes back in time to the year 1947, along with Allison (Salli Richardson-Whitfield), Jo (Erica Cerra), Henry (Joe Morton) and Fargo (Neil Grayston). With the assistance of scientist Trevor Grant (James Callis), and are able to get back to present-day Eureka.But... some things have changed. Jo is the security chief of Global Dynamics and never dated Zane, Kevin is not autistic, Andy the robot is Carter's new deputy, Henry is married to a woman he doesn't know, and Fargo is now the director of Global Dynamics. Oh yes, and Grant has come forward in time with them.As they try to adjust to this new timeline, they have to deal with mysterious power surges, a zombie-style rage infection, a super-oxygen infestation, random teleportation (from 1947!), stalkerish A.I.s, people turning into stone statues, and hallucinations of people from the past. And Dr. Grant starts discovering that the future isn't all it's cracked up to be.I was starting to lose faith in "Eureka" after the disappointing Season 3.5, which was basically a bunch of standalone episodes. And while "time travel ripples" sounds like a cheap way of shaking things up, it actually works quite well here -- the writers spend the entire season exploring the repercussions of time travel.It sounds kind of grim, but there are some fun moments keeping it light -- particularly a cute Wall-E-esque robot, or Carter throwing the despised Fargo a ravening horde. The one real disappointment is the Eureka crossover -- it's not really BAD, but Claudia Donovan's visit is kinda anticlimactic because... she doesn't do anything except ogle the machinery and make out with Fargo.Colin Ferguson continues to be charmingly down-to-earth, even as Carter gets enmeshed in a very tense love triangle with Grant and Allison. Also fun: the writers take some clever pokes at Carter's role in the show ("Hello, I'm Sheriff Carter! I'm going to save the day with my everyman logic! Ha ha ha!").But all the characters get some solid development -- Jo is in turmoil over the loss of Zane, Allison becomes even more of a fierce mama bear now that her son is normal, and Henry starts falling in love with the wife he doesn't even know (although this happens a bit too fast). Oh, and Sheriff Andy is back as Deputy Andy, reciting bad poetry and suffering massive damage."Eureka Season 4.0" pumps some new life into this quirky sci-fi show, and rearranges some of the key players. Good stuff!

reviewText: As others have pointed out, this collection only includes half of a season, but that doesn't particularly bother me (especially since I watch it on Netflix in HD). This is my favorite season of Eureka so far... and that's saying something, since I love them all! I really enjoyed the story line that beings in the first episode. It involves many of the show's fan favorites traveling back in time, where they witnessed the founding of the Eureka community. This plot line continues throughout the season, and it's truly riveting. The Eureka gang is always getting into big trouble with their wacky devices, and this time they've REALLY outdone themselves.Sheriff Carter continues his evolution as SyFy's best leading man of all time. His charisma, humor, and goofiness only continue to improve! This season also featured the brief return of a couple of HUGE fan favorites, which was great for us. The producers and writers of Eureka know what the term "fan service" means!

reviewText: This pill is bitter, yo, what with EUREKA getting the yank once the upcoming fifth season is done. In the meantime, here's EUREKA SEASON 4.0 which I hope more people don't misconstrue as the full season collected (the "Season 4.0" tag - as opposed to just "Season 4" - is sort of a hint). Speaking for myself, these particular half-a-season releases are perfectly fine. I'm one of them gents what can't wait for the full season DVD to come out; it's too long a wait. And, like someone here already said, those assuming that this DVD set release contains the entire season's episodes when Syfy hasn't even aired all of them yet - well, give me a hit of what you're smoking. Otherwise, step off. EUREKA SEASON 4.0 is very reasonably priced, considering you do get nine episodes (ten, if you count the extended version of "Founder's Day"), plus bonus features. This isn't one of those messed-up DVD sets which only present four measly episodes a pop.EUREKA's writing think tank got their clever on, thus circumventing the malaise that sometimes grips a show rolling on its third or fourth season. Season 4's opener, "Founder's Day," shuffles the deck, flips the scenario, makes me gibber like a giddy aunt. "Founder's Day" is a marvelous time travel story. Thanks to a rash of solar flares, during the Founder's Day holiday, five of our main characters are catapulted back to the year 1947, when the hidden town of Eureka - back then more a rough military camp than an established town of geniuses - was first finding its legs. Our cast survives 1947 but then returns to an unfamiliar present-day Eureka. You have to give it up to the writers' reinventing of the show. It certainly hits that refresh button. Maybe the best bit is what happens to Fargo.Season 4 marks the return of several old favorites (treacherous psychologist Beverly Barlowe, the amiable Sheriff Andy, and Zoe Carter who shows up for several eps). Meanwhile, the tremendous James Callis ("Baltar" to you) signs on as new cast member "Dr. Old Spice" (heh) and serves as a foil to Sheriff Jack Carter. And if you're one of them fools for romance and had been pulling for Sheriff Carter to get his love life together... well, practice those contented sighs. Conversely, Deputy Jo Lupo learns that, in this new reality, she and her boyfriend Zane had never gotten jiggy with it. I love Jo Lupo's personal arc in this season. Erica Cerra does that unrequited thing pretty well, balancing her no-nonsense toughness with an appealing emotional vulnerability.The cast hasn't eased off on being wonderful. There's still that air of unpredictability with each episode. As they say, in a secret community flaunting the world's most dangerous minds, anything can - and does - happen, from a calming ray reversing its purpose and turning the GD staff into homicidal zombies to intelligent AI exhibiting emotions to an outbreak of petrification. The playfulness is prevalent. And it just never gets old that Sheriff Carter always assumes this nonplussed expression whenever scientific exposition is going down (Colin Ferguson continues to be the bedrock of the show). The science run amok that frequently plagues Eureka is still based, however tenuously, on actual science or scientific theory. So maybe I'm soaking in knowledge whilst I'm watching one of my favorite shows.I'd normally mention which were my favorite episodes but they're all quite excellent. Maybe "Founder's Day" and "A New World" are a smidge above. "Crossing Over" is EUREKA's crossover ep with WAREHOUSE 13 and has the Warehouse's resident tech, Claudia Donovan, visiting Global Dynamics. I hope to heck that this crosspolination of Syfy shows continues and becomes tradition. That wouldn't suck at all. And "Stoned," while a very good episode, is elevated by Joe Morton's surprise song rendition of a Thomas Dolby classic.But, okay, I am pretty bummed that episode 12, "Reprise" - which guest stars the awesomely awesome Felicia Day - won't be available until the Season 4.5 DVD set.Bonus material for the EUREKA: SEASON 4.0 set: Deleted Scenes for eight episodes (only "Founder's Day - Extended Version" and "the Ex-Files" don't have deleted scenes; the regular "Founder's Day" version does get a deleted scene); a gag reel; "13.1," the WAREHOUSE 13 crossover episode; "In the Beginning: Camp Eureka 1947" - an inside look at the design of Camp Eureka 1947 (00:05:23 minutes long); and the "Founder's Day" Extended Version Filmmakers Commentary.
summary: "Hello, I'm Sheriff Carter. I'm gonna save the day with my everyman logic. Bwa-ha-ha."

reviewText: Eureka the fourth season seems to be a little more convoluted than the other seasons.  In their attempt to add a new twist to the series the writers made it difficult to follow.  The crew get transported back to 1947 and can not find their way home.  Then-all of a sudden- they are home.  Then the story line gets complicated because characters that we have not seen before are in the story.  Lives were changed but we had no idea of what their lives were.  Then to make bad writing even worse we never know if they are speaking from their 1947 experiences or present day.  You may be asking then why give it 4 stars?  I really like the creativity and imagination that goes into the show.  When you settle of the fact that not everything will be clear then it is a blast to watch.  My opinion my rating my reasons.  That's all folks.knight68

reviewText: This show continues to amuse and entertain me. Not overly technical, nor is it a brainiac's bible, but it is just scientific enough for these things to happen now and in the near future. Along the way however, several other character shine and amuse, so the show doesn't seem to get old.

reviewText: I love this Series, it would not even bother me if they came out with a 2-disc set with only 1 episode on it only featuring Joe Morton -- I Would Still Love This Series.  It's intelligent, funny, original, well acted and, and, All That.  But this season, they've started doing what most all mediocre movies and TV shows do that can't stand on their good writing and performances:  they use "bad" words.  Why?  This show has everything, oh except potty words and now when a youngster sits down and starts watching I get distracted with the giggles from the kids....Ohhhh, they said a bad word, or, why did that girl call the guys, "bitches"?I don't know, honey...let's turn the channel and watch sex in the 'burbs, season 167 or the history channel:  America's 57th State.(I'm not a prude, the language just brings absolutely nothing to this show, nothing but distractions from this AAA++ show!)Too bad they don't think there is enough quality associated with these episodes that, dam* I don't know, a bunch of nerdy, highly intelligent geeks trying to attract the pre-teens with do-do words?  It even "feels" strange that a hi-tech, scientist/research/PhD/inventor says, sheeeiiit, where did I put that flux-de-germinating, hi-temp molecular do-dad?  It just doesn't work.
summary: Why Start with the *^*k*ng Bad Language, B**c*eS?

reviewText: The first two seasons of Eureka were outstanding and original.  Beginning in the third, however a sense of "been there done that" began to creep into each episode.  Even the actors appeared to be losing interest.  But happily, season 4 was just the infusion of freshness this series needed.  Taking our main characters back in time, then sending them back to the present but in an alternate reality was stroke of genius, allowing the writers to reinvent many of the characters and their relationships, giving us some fresh takes on what was getting oh so stale.  James Callis (aka Baltar from Battlestar Galactica) is a welcome addition to the cast this go around, as are the guest appearances of Wil Wheaton, the cross-over episode with Warehouse 13, and the return of sadly missed characters Nathan Stark, Beverly Barlowe, and Jim Taggart.Now, if only they can get Jordan Hinson back into the regular cast . . . this show would be perfect again!
summary: A series-saving season if I ever saw one.
